  "text": "The current finding is similar to work by Schooler (Schooler & EngstlerSchooler, 1990; [CITATION_1] which demonstrated that verbal processes can lead people to focus on some aspects of a visual task at the expense of others. In the case of glass tilting, people focussed on spatial outcomes rather than allowing their knowledge of rate to drive their imagery. Consequently, their spatial beliefs usurped the functional, dynamic component of imagery. These results, however, should not be taken to imply that imagery is always better than beliefs for simple physical problems (cf. [CITATION_2] . [CITATION_3] , for example, showed that beliefs enable people to compensate for illusory tilts in the Piagetian water level task. Rather, the results indicate that physical imagery can be usurped by beliefs that specify spatial outcomes.",
